The paper proposes a new format for representing combinatorial constrained problems, which is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The use of optimization, cost functions, and probabilistic reasoning suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The focus on constraint solvers and the use of arrays of variables suggests a connection to data structures (cs.DS) and programming languages (cs.PL). The emphasis on testing and comparing algorithms suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG) and software engineering (cs.SE).
